The proof is rigorous. The key steps: bounding f(N) for odd and even non-multiples of 3; computing f for even multiples of 3 based on v2 and divisibility by 5; analyzing the iteration on exponents. The case where a1 is even and divisible by 3, with v2 even or v3 too small, leads to termination because the exponent of 2 eventually becomes 0 (making the number odd) or the exponent of 3 becomes 0 (making the number not divisible by 3), and then the strictly decreasing property ensures a prime or prime square appears. The condition for infinite sequence is derived correctly. The converse is verified by iterating the map until a fixed point is reached. All assumptions are justified, and no gaps remain.
